WHEREAS, a unified parish-wide approach could strengthen emergency
preparedness, improve FEMA reimbursement compliance, create economies of scale, and
allow for long-term infrastructure investments such as debris staging areas, transfer stations,
recycling centers, and hardened landfill facilities; and
WHEREAS, resilient waste and debris management systems are a critical component
of public health, environmental protection, economic recovery, and infrastructure stability
during and after disasters.
THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
Legislature of Louisiana does hereby urge and request the Department of Environmental
Quality, the Governor's Office of Homeland Security and Emergency Preparedness, the
Ouachita Parish Police Jury, and all incorporated municipalities within Ouachita Parish to
collaboratively conduct a comprehensive study to address parish-wide consolidation of
services, disaster debris management and FEMA compliance, resiliency and infrastructure
improvements, and governance and funding models.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the study of consolidation of services shall
include consideration of the following:
(1) Centralized residential and commercial trash collection.
(2) Parish-wide debris hauling and disposal contracts.
(3) Unified billing and service administration models.
(4) Cost savings and rate stabilization impacts.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the study of disaster debris management and
FEMA compliance shall include consideration of the following:
(1) Pre-event debris removal contracts.
(2) Designated debris management and staging sites.
(3) FEMA documentation protocols.
(4) Rapid deployment cleanup frameworks.
(5) Public-private partnership opportunities.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the study of resiliency and infrastructure
improvements shall include consideration of the following:
(1) Hardened landfill and transfer station planning.
(2) Recycling and waste diversion systems.
